  abstract = {Abstract             This chapter lays out those elements of the Roman system that underpinned its strategic execution. It starts with a discussion of Rome’s extensive system of frontier defense, which allowed it to conserve troops when on defense and provided a covered zone to concentrate force for offensive operations. The frontier networks also made it possible for Rome to control trade and diplomatic relations across their frontiers, often to surprising extents—several hundred miles or more. This frontier system was supported by thousands of miles of paved roads that made it possible for Rome to rapidly move legions to threatened frontiers or provinces. Just as crucially, this extensive road system made it possible to feed the legions in whatever part of the Empire they were concentrated.},
